T1  - External Networking and Internal Firm Governance
AU  - FRACASSI, CESARE
AU  - TATE, GEOFFREY
Y1  - 2012/02/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2011.01706.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 153
EP  - 194
VL  - 67
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2011.01706.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We use panel data on S&P 1500 companies to identify external network connections between directors and CEOs. We find that firms with more powerful CEOs are more likely to appoint directors with ties to the CEO. Using changes in board composition due to director death and retirement for identification, we find that CEO-director ties reduce firm value, particularly in the absence of other governance mechanisms to substitute for board oversight. Moreover, firms with more CEO-director ties engage in more value-destroying acquisitions. Overall, our results suggest that network ties with the CEO weaken the intensity of board monitoring.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Information Disclosure and Corporate Governance
AU  - HERMALIN, BENJAMIN E.
AU  - WEISBACH, MICHAEL S.
Y1  - 2012/02/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2011.01710.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 195
EP  - 233
VL  - 67
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2011.01710.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Public policy discussions typically favor greater corporate disclosure as a way to reduce firms' agency problems. This argument is incomplete because it overlooks that better disclosure regimes can also aggravate agency problems and related costs, including executive compensation. Consequently, a point can exist beyond which additional disclosure decreases firm value. Holding all else equal, we further show that larger firms will adopt stricter disclosure rules than smaller firms and firms with better disclosure will employ more able management. We show that mandated increases in disclosure could, in part, explain recent increases in both CEO compensation and CEO turnover rates.
ER  - 

