T1  - The Value of Investment Banking Relationships: Evidence from the Collapse of Lehman Brothers
AU  - FERNANDO, CHITRU S.
AU  - MAY, ANTHONY D.
AU  - MEGGINSON, WILLIAM L.
Y1  - 2012/02/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2011.01711.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 235
EP  - 270
VL  - 67
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2011.01711.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We examine the long-standing question of whether firms derive value from investment bank relationships by studying how the Lehman collapse affected industrial firms that received underwriting, advisory, analyst, and market-making services from Lehman. Equity underwriting clients experienced an abnormal return of around ?5%, on average, in the 7 days surrounding Lehman's bankruptcy, amounting to $23 billion in aggregate risk-adjusted losses. Losses were especially severe for companies that had stronger and broader security underwriting relationships with Lehman or were smaller, younger, and more financially constrained. Other client groups were not adversely affected.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - When It Pays to Pay Your Investment Banker: New Evidence on the Role of Financial Advisors in M&As
AU  - GOLUBOV, ANDREY
AU  - PETMEZAS, DIMITRIS
AU  - TRAVLOS, NICKOLAOS G.
Y1  - 2012/02/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2011.01712.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 271
EP  - 311
VL  - 67
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2011.01712.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We provide new evidence on the role of financial advisors in M&As. Contrary to prior studies, top-tier advisors deliver higher bidder returns than their non-top-tier counterparts but in public acquisitions only, where the advisor reputational exposure and required skills set are relatively larger. This translates into a $65.83 million shareholder gain for an average bidder. The improvement comes from top-tier advisors' ability to identify more synergistic combinations and to get a larger share of synergies to accrue to bidders. Consistent with the premium price?premium quality equilibrium, top-tier advisors charge premium fees in these transactions.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Why Does the Law Matter? Investor Protection and Its Effects on Investment, Finance, and Growth
AU  - MCLEAN, R. DAVID
AU  - ZHANG, TIANYU
AU  - ZHAO, MENGXIN
Y1  - 2012/02/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2011.01713.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 313
EP  - 350
VL  - 67
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2011.01713.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Investor protection is associated with greater investment sensitivity to q and lower investment sensitivity to cash flow. Finance plays a role in causing these effects; in countries with strong investor protection, external finance increases more strongly with q, and declines more strongly with cash flow. We further find that q and cash flow sensitivities are associated with ex post investment efficiency; investment predicts growth and profits more strongly in countries with greater q sensitivities and lower cash flow sensitivities. The paper's findings are broadly consistent with investor protection promoting accurate share prices, reducing financial constraints, and encouraging efficient investment.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Family-Controlled Firms and Informed Trading: Evidence from Short Sales
AU  - ANDERSON, RONALD C.
AU  - REEB, DAVID M.
AU  - ZHAO, WANLI
Y1  - 2012/02/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2011.01714.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 351
EP  - 385
VL  - 67
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2011.01714.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We investigate the relation between organization structure and the information content of short sales, focusing on founder- and heir-controlled firms. Our analysis indicates that family-controlled firms experience substantially higher abnormal short sales prior to negative earnings shocks than nonfamily firms. Supplementary testing indicates that family control characteristics intensify informed short selling. Further analysis suggests that daily short-sale interest in family firms contains useful information in forecasting stock returns; however, we find no discernable effect for nonfamily firms. This analysis provides compelling evidence that informed trading via short sales occurs more readily in family firms than in nonfamily firms.
ER  - 

